s/working-sessions/moving-from-graphs-to-maps/</guid><description>About this talk: Each component in a Wardley map is classified by the value it has to the customer or user and by the maturity of that component, ranging from custom-made to commodity. Components are drawn as nodes on a graph with value on the y-axis and commodity on the x-axis. A custom-made component with no direct value to the user would sit at the bottom-left of such a graph while a commodity component with high direct value to the user would sit at the top-right of such a graph.</description></item><item><title>PSD &amp; Squads &amp; Tribes &amp; Team Topologies</title><link>https://open-security-summit.org/tracks/wardley-maps/working-sessions/team-topologies/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://open-security-summit.org/tracks/wardley-maps/working-sessions/team-topologies/</guid><description/></item><item><title>Real World Wardley Maps</title><link>https://open-security-summit.org/tracks/wardley-maps/working-sessions/real-world-wardley-maps/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://open-security-summit.org/tracks/wardley-maps/working-sessions/real-world-wardley-maps/</guid><description/></item><item><title>Risk Mapping - Applying Risk overlay with maps and security decision making</title><link>https://open-security-summit.org/tracks/wardley-maps/working-sessions/risk-overlay-with-maps/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://open-security-summit.org/tracks/wardley-maps/working-sessions/risk-overlay-with-maps/</guid><description/></item><item><title>Security implications of the isolation and terrorism</title><link>https://open-security-summit.org/tracks/wardley-maps/working-sessions/security-implications-isolation-and-terrorism/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://open-security-summit.org/tracks/wardley-maps/working-sessions/security-implications-isolation-and-terrorism/</